---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="The philosophy and pedagogical approach behind The Number Garden."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>A garden is not built by force.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The Number Garden is built around a simple conviction: deep learning
        does not come from coercion, compliance, or performance. It emerges
        when curiosity is alive, when attention has somewhere to go, and when
        the conditions are right for real engagement to take root.
      </p>
    </div>

    <aside class="hero-card" aria-label="Core ideas of The Number Garden">
      <p class="card-label">Core ideas</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Growth shaped by conditions rather than coercion</li>
        <li>Learning done by the learner</li>
        <li>Rigorous play, not shallow entertainment</li>
        <li>Access widened through culture as well as logistics</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Philosophy</p>
      <h2>A philosophy of learning.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="content-stack">
      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Many ways to grow</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          There are many ways to grow a garden and many ways to grow crops. One
          approach relies on tilling the soil, planting uniform rows of
          monoculture crops, and applying enough force to maximize output.
        </p>
        <p class="section-copy">
          Another approach is to nurture the conditions in which life can
          thrive, so that abundance can emerge naturally. If you walk through a
          forest or a jungle, there is abundance. Nature does not need to be
          forced into life. It grows when there is light, and when air and
          water can move through the soil.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>The same is true of human learning</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          The same is true of human learning. We do not believe children need
          rows of desks or submission to authority in order to learn deeply.
        </p>
        <p class="section-copy">
          We believe children can be invited into environments rich enough,
          beautiful enough, and alive enough that they lose themselves in
          joyful problem solving.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>How learning happens here</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          Learning happens as a result of something done by the learner, not as
          a result of something done by the teacher. The role of the teacher is
          to create the conditions for learning to happen.
        </p>
        <p class="section-copy">
          At The Number Garden, that means curating mathematical gems that can
          ignite deep engagement, then getting out of the way enough for real
          noticing, conjecturing, questioning, and explanation to begin.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Rigorous play</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          Play is not the opposite of rigor. Some of the deepest mathematical
          pleasure comes from wrestling with a problem, seeing structure emerge,
          and finding a path that feels both elegant and true.
        </p>
        <p class="section-copy">
          The Number Garden is a curated learning environment, informed by
          decades of experience of rigorous play.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Widening the door</h3>
        <p class="section-copy">
          We want to help build a mathematical culture with a wider entrance:
          one that makes room for different tempos, prior experiences, and ways
          of participating, with lower floors and higher ceilings. Access is
          not only a question of accommodations or logistics. It also lives in
          tone, pacing, dignity, and belonging.
        </p>
        <p class="section-copy">
          In that sense, access is not separate from the philosophy. It is part
          of what it means to create conditions in which more people can come
          alive to mathematics.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-accent" id="pedagogy-in-action">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Pedagogy in Action</p>
      <h2>Here is one glimpse of what that can look like.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      Diffy Squares is one of my favorite mathematical gems because it makes the
      philosophy tangible. A learner begins with four numbers at the corners of
      a square and keeps taking the differences between neighboring corners.
      Very quickly, the problem becomes full of pattern, surprise, and
      conjecture.
    </p>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      This is the kind of task I mean when I talk about rigorous play. It has a
      low floor, a high ceiling, and enough structure to invite real thinking
      without forcing the learner down a single narrow path.
    </p>

    <div class="card-grid" aria-label="What Diffy Squares reveals about the pedagogy">
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Notice and wonder</h3>
        <p>
          The learner starts by observing what changes, what repeats, and what
          feels surprising.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Conjecture and test</h3>
        <p>
          Patterns lead naturally to guesses, experiments, and better
          questions.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Explain and refine</h3>
        <p>
          The experience invites learners to articulate why something seems to
          happen and whether it always does.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="inline-links">
      <a class="card-link" href="/about/diffy-squares/">
        Try the full Diffy Squares experience
      </a>
      <a class="card-link" href="/family-visit/">
        Book a family visit
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
